<EXTRAINFO>Bankruptcy for U.S. automaker GM becomes almost certain after bondholder offers fail</EXTRAINFO>
<TEXT><s id="0">Bankruptcy for U.S. automaker GM becomes almost certain after bondholder offers fail</s><s id="1">May 28 , 2009</s><s id="2">The United States automobile manufacturing firm General Motors <EVENT eid="e117">announced</EVENT> on Wednesday that most of its bondholders did not exchange GM 's US$ 27 billion debt for a ten percent share in the company 's stock .</s><s id="3">The automaker , in financial straits , <EVENT eid="e129">has</EVENT> a June 1 deadline to finish a government restructuring plan that includes plant closures and other debt reduction measures .</s><s id="4">U.S. President Barack Obama 's administration said it would not give more financial aid to the firm unless 90 % of GM 's bondholders would agree on compromises that would significantly reduce the firm 's costs .</s><s id="5">`` The principal amount of notes tendered was substantially less than the amount <EVENT eid="e128">required</EVENT> by GM to satisfy the debt reduction requirement , '' GM <EVENT eid="e108">said</EVENT> in a statement .</s><s id="6">`` They said no .</s><s id="7">That 's it .</s><s id="8">They <EVENT eid="e116">tried</EVENT> .</s><s id="9">That 's why they 're going to have to <EVENT eid="e114">file</EVENT> for bankruptcy , '' said a university professor from the University of Michigan who specializes in bankruptcy .</s></TEXT>
